NOTES:
    1. At first we turn tools and usage of their API into SKILLS (ease process of integrating them into tolls for coding agent)
    2. Added d3js-graph-visualization SKILL from the ARE-d3js template: covers radial + force graph layouts (d3 v4), with standalone runnable snippets placed as resource examples (resources/force-graph.html, resources/radial-graph.html) plus the full template.html for reference.
        * Generalized the edge 'sent' (sentiment) field in the d3js-graph-visualization snippets to a generic 'rel' relation label with a configurable RELATION_COLORS map (sentiment is now just one example config); template.html kept as the verbatim sentiment-specific source.
    3. Added callbacks to offload tool output to artifact store.
    4. Added support for artifact inputs in tools (before_tool_callback to inflate them into the inline lists the tools expect).
    5. Found bug in non-registered pairs tool. 
    6. Added thinking bubble to the UI. The default asset of SKILLS for agent does not cover a work with event model. We integrate 08_event.md into adk-event SKILL from the ADK from tutorial here: https://github.com/Kjdragan/google-adk-tutorial/blob/main/08_event.md
    7. Added the `output` tool: it builds the visualization graph deterministically from the classify_relations artifact and persists the finished AgentResponse as a session artifact, so the model no longer hand-writes the (long, error-prone) graph into set_model_response. The server prefers that artifact (by name+version, turn-safe) as the authoritative final response.
    8. Added a two-layer empty-response fallback so the user always sees something on termination. 
        Agent level: an after_model_callback (ensure_nonempty_response) catches empty model turns (finishReason STOP with no content/tool call) and substitutes a readable retry message — works in every runner, incl. adk web. 
        Server level: _ensure_message guarantees a non-blank message and recovers the output-built graph; kept task-agnostic by comparing the structured output against a defaults-only schema instance instead of referencing graph-specific fields.
    10. Added progress reporting for long-running tools (classify_relations).
        - Added a progress bar to the UI.
        - Fixed "Event loop is closed" on the 2nd+ classify_relations call. Root cause: `_get_llm` was @lru_cache'd, so the bulk-chain provider adapter (and its lazily-created httpx.AsyncClient) was reused across calls; that async client binds to the event loop that first drives it, but each run uses its own short-lived loop (see `_run_in_isolated_loop`) which is closed afterwards — so the cached client referenced a dead loop on the next run.
    11. Simplified the classify_relations prompt schema from a 2-step CoT (reasoning -> label) to a single label-only prompt (halves LLM calls per pair).
    12. Moved the agent's giant inline INSTRUCTION into ADK 2.0 Skills (SkillToolset + load_skill_from_dir, ADK 2.3.0 in .venv/py3.10) so the heavy workflow text stays out of the base context window until needed (L1 description always in context, L2 body loaded on demand via the load_skill tool).
        - Base instruction is now task-agnostic: only agent identity, a skill-first working style (discover via list_skills, load via load_skill, prefer documented tools), and the always-on structured-output contract (set_model_response) — no NER/graph/layout specifics. Dropped from ~5KB to ~800 chars.
        - Split the workflow into two non-intersecting skills under src/skills/ (each its own dir; dir name must match frontmatter name):
            * arexplorer-workflow: the tool pipeline + artifact offload/inflate mechanics (produces the data/graph).
            * arexplorer-response: the client-side reply contract (set_model_response / AgentResponse shape, message/graph/layout, when to leave graph empty).
        - Removed all inter-skill cross-references; orchestration lives solely in the base instruction so skills stay self-contained.
        - Rewrote both skill descriptions per good-description guidance: imperative ("Use this skill when..."), user-intent over implementation, pushy about implicit triggers (e.g. even when the user never says "NER"/"sentiment"/"graph"), concise and under the 1024-char spec limit.